 the whole group. Robinson tracks this collectivistic thinking through a series of comparative considerations using a theory that draws impetus from Arne Naess's "ecosophical" deep ecology and from work on rhetoric powered by affective ecologies, but with details of the theory drawn equally from Mencius and Aristotle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric)xHistoryxTo 1500xCriticism, interpretation, etcxHistory. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438461083423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438461083/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles